1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:08,029
In this video we are going to learn six design pattern which is the command query responsibility segregation

2
00:00:08,029 --> 00:00:08,660
pattern.

3
00:00:09,800 --> 00:00:14,570
Six is one of the important pattern when querying between microservices.

4
00:00:14,600 --> 00:00:21,890
We can use six design pattern in order to avoid complex queries to get rid of the inefficient joins.

5
00:00:23,400 --> 00:00:28,380
Seacrest stands for the Command and Query Responsibility segregation pattern.

6
00:00:28,410 --> 00:00:34,530
Basically, this pattern separates read and write operations with separating databases.

7
00:00:36,490 --> 00:00:41,950
The main idea is that we can divide the application operation into two separate categories.

8
00:00:41,980 --> 00:00:43,780
The first one is commands.

9
00:00:43,810 --> 00:00:47,620
These commands are changing the state of data into application.

10
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:49,900
And the second one is the queries.

11
00:00:49,930 --> 00:00:56,290
These queries are handling complex join operations are returning a result, and don't change the state

12
00:00:56,290 --> 00:00:58,090
of the data into the application.

13
00:00:59,710 --> 00:01:06,880
In large scale microservice architectures, it needs to manage high volume data requirements for this

14
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:07,990
kind of use cases.

15
00:01:07,990 --> 00:01:15,340
Monolithic approaches like single database for services can cause bottlenecks for complex and large

16
00:01:15,340 --> 00:01:17,290
scale microservice architectures.

17
00:01:17,290 --> 00:01:23,440
We can use both SQS and event sourcing patterns to improve application performance.

18
00:01:24,190 --> 00:01:31,000
SQS offers two separate read and write data that provide to maximize query performance and scalability.

19
00:01:32,950 --> 00:01:35,410
Let's think about the monolithic applications.

20
00:01:35,410 --> 00:01:42,340
Most of the time we have one databases, and this database should respond to both query and update operations.

21
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:49,690
That means a single database is both working for complex join operations and also perform Crud operations.

22
00:01:51,490 --> 00:01:58,840
But if the application goes more complex, this query and Crud operations will be also going to be unmanageable

23
00:01:58,840 --> 00:01:59,620
situation.

24
00:02:00,190 --> 00:02:06,610
In example of reading database, if your application required some query that needs to join more than

25
00:02:06,610 --> 00:02:12,070
one table, this will lock the database due to latency of query computation.

26
00:02:13,620 --> 00:02:20,250
Also, if you give example of writing database when performing the Crud operations, we would need to

27
00:02:20,250 --> 00:02:23,640
make complex validations and process long business logics.

28
00:02:23,640 --> 00:02:26,640
So this will cause the lock database operations.

29
00:02:27,550 --> 00:02:33,580
So reading and writing database has different approaches that we can define different strategies to

30
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:34,900
handle that operation.

31
00:02:35,560 --> 00:02:42,940
In order to that, SQL is offered to use separation of concerns, principles and separate reading database

32
00:02:42,940 --> 00:02:45,970
and writing database with two databases.

33
00:02:46,060 --> 00:02:52,450
By this way, we can even use different database for reading and writing database types, like using

34
00:02:52,450 --> 00:02:56,830
NoSQL database for reading and using relational database for Crud operations.

35
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:06,250
Mostly read database uses NoSQL databases with Denormalized data, which generates from the right databases,

36
00:03:06,250 --> 00:03:13,660
and the right database uses relational databases with fully normalized and supports strong data consistency.

